role it plays in experiences of beauty. This volume sheds new light on the conception of disinterested pleasure from the perspectives of both Kant scholarship and contemporary aesthetics. In the first part, the focus is on Kant’s theory of beauty as grounded on the conception of disinterested pleasure. In the second part, disinterested pleasure is investigated in the light of contemporary debates on beauty. The volume clarifies the meaning, role, and implications of one of the most influential conceptions in traditional as well as contemporary approaches to beauty.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAesthetics, Moderny21st century. 4aAntirealismus. 4aKant, Immanuel. 4aÄsthetischer Realismus. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aDisinterested pleasure.  aKant's aeshtetics.  aaesthetic realism and anti-realism.  aphilosophy of beauty.1 aBerger, Larissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Larissa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGorodeisky, Keren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuyer, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHilgers, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcIver Lopes, Dominic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmalzried, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShelley, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVelotti, Stefano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWenzel, Christian Helmut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZan